In article <3484.Jun1719.39.5293@silverton.berkeley.edu>, 
djb@silverton.berkeley.edu (D. J. Bernstein) writes:

> In article <strnlghtC85sA6.78K@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
>> Both MacRipem (probably Ripem real soon now) and TISPEM involve
>> certification and certification authorities. That adds additional confidence
>> that PGP lacks, since what passes for certification is entirely ad hoc
>> there.
> 
> The PEM model of key ``certification'' allows one man, Jim Bidzos, to 
> singlehandedly destroy the entire PEM communications system in a matter 
> of days. What were you saying about confidence?
> 
> ---Dan

That is hyperbole.

Our ARNES PCA (policy certification authority) works independently of 
any PCA Internet might set up. Thus if 'Bidzos' PCA gets compromised I 
may not trust your public key, but those in other areas are still ok and 
PEM service would go on.

Please read the data sheet on RSA Data Sec. certification machine.

